# In fact, yes.

I found that the wikipedia page for [position operator](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Position_operator) nicely shows this.

Take that a normalized wavefunction $\psi$'s square modulus
$$
|\psi|^2=\psi^*\psi
$$
represents the probability density of finding a particle at some position x.
So then,
$$
\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}|\psi|^2dx=1
$$
and the probability of finding the particle in a range is
$$
\pi_X(\psi)([a,b])=\int^{b}_{a}dx|\psi|^2
$$
The expected value of measurement of the position would be
$$
\braket{X}_\psi=\int_\Bbb{R}x|\psi|^2dx=\int_\Bbb{R}\psi^*(x\psi)dx=\braket{\psi|X(\psi)}
$$
::: {.callout-note}
Why is $x|\psi|^2=\psi^*(x\psi)$?
*This is simply a commutative + associative property, because $x$ is not an operator here.*
:::

::: {.callout-note}
Is $x\psi=X(\psi)?$
:::

::: {.callout-note}
Observe that $\int_\Bbb{R}x|\psi|^2dx$ is just a first moment integral. We're taking the "center of mass" of the probability distribution.
:::



# Bra Kets

A **ket** is a vector in a complex vector space.

A **bra** is a linear form $f:V\rightarrow \Bbb{C}$. It maps a vector to a complex number.
* So then it can also be thought of as a row vector.

::: {.callout-note}
How are these related to functions if they are vectors?
Functions are infinite-valued vectors
Functionals like the Lagrangian or Differentiation are infinite matrices that transform functions into other functions
:::

::: {.callout-question}
So then, what are row vectors as functions? What are dot products of functions? 
 In fact, this has been discussed before.
 It's the infinite sum of every element of the functions, 
 $$ \int dxf(x)g(x) = \braket{f,g} $$
:::


So then the ***braket*** is the inner product between functions.
$$ \braket{f^{*}|g} $$
The ***braket*** notation can be used for vector spaces with an *involution* operation.
Then, the dot product must have the first argument be a conjugate.

A row vector is also a conjugate (covector). Covectors aren't vectors in the traditional sense. We can think of them as functions that operate on vectors. Applying a row vector to a vector produces... voila! A scalar!


